segments.text: For the TVMA, you know, but that was more, I interviewed you a little bit for the TVMA, so I thought I'd just like to get a little resume of your life, talking about you, you know, not necessarily TVMA.
Why don't you give a little resume of your career?
You were born right in this area, weren't you?
Oh, actually I was born in Austin, Texas.
What was your birthday?
July the 27th, 1915.
Born in Austin, right almost in the shadow of the Capitol.
When we went to school, we'd go across town and I spent an hour running through the rotundas of the Austin Capitol and visiting during the legislative session, all that kind of stuff.
And see, my father was a printer.
He came from just the other side of De Leon, out in that true mid-central Texas.
Very few people know about De Leon and Eastland and Sisko and through that country.
But my father was printing a newspaper by the time he was 12 years old.
My grandfather traveled for a silver moon candy company.
And every time he'd get into some smaller town, a little time to spare, he'd buy their scrap type at the printing office.
Just did paper bags, you know.
It took them a lot of time before they'd get around and they'd have to sort it, put it back in its proper places so the typesetter handled it almost like a typewriter.
He had a big case type thing and he could feel A, B, C, Ds, E, F, Gs.
He could just grab them and
and fill his plate by hand-spelling with those linotype-prepared lead figures.
Well, a very long story short, Father came to Austin with the Austin American States newspaper.
And he was picked up by Mr.
Sticks, Edgar Sticks.
Steck was kind of an entrepreneur, and one of his desires was he'd like to help print a bit.
And so he and my father together founded the Steck Print Company in Austin.
And of course, Steck is known statewide for preparing most of the checks that go to the banks and insurance policies.
And back during the centennial year of Texas, they published for the first time.
manuscripts, copied manuscripts.
Today they're known as Steck Vaughn.
Vaughn was pretty big in the publishing business and he took over and it's still in existence.
But my father-in-office, Steck Printing Company, was right downtown and we would visit him and maybe ride with him home and so forth while I was in Austin schools.
And just before I went to A&M,
My family moved over on the south side of Austin in what's called Travis Park.
And there was a Mr. Norwood.
Had quite an estate over beyond this.
The expressway now runs almost through his property.
That forms into the expressway through Austin and so on.
Now, I worked for him during the summers.
looking after his swimming pool.
A lifeguard, pool manager, and so forth.
He had a private pool.
And he got in trouble with income tax people, and he lost everything except his homestead.
And he had to open his pool to the public.
So while I was babysitting this pool, there was a story in the newspaper about Mark Francis, dean of the veterinary school in Texas A&M.
I took that paper home and told my parents, I'm going to be a veterinarian.
That's the first ink that I ever had, and that's how I got started.
And the following fall, I went to A&M, 1933, in September, and graduated in 1937, June.
And almost had the same inspiration, I decided just out of the clear blue that
I liked New Belfast, and so within a few hours' time of the state board, I was in New Belfast, Texas, in practice, still in June of 1937.
You know, at the time you began practice, did they still inflate udders for milk fever and that sort of thing?
Well, right off the verge, the quackery is what we called it back at that stage.
of inflate the udder.
But that did help.
It seemed to have some effect.
The difficulty was the methods they were using.
They used everything from bicycle pumps all the way through.
It was unsanitary.
They would seal it by tying it with just most any kind of boundary twine or anything.
But didn't didn't licensed veterinarians do that also?
Well, yes.

You know, there was a very, very narrow line at that time in the minds of young veterinary students, which is still close to today, that that old licensed practitioner was just a step above the quacks.
And there wasn't a great deal of respect out for the older practitioner because these new faggots
drugs and the drug development, that is, you know, the first advent of the detail man who would come around and explain the products and so forth.
Veterinarians owe a lot of their education in that period of time to the detail people.
who went back to the home office, you know, and came back with how they manufactured ship and how they manufactured backgrounds.
You know, give you a more of a practical insight on what you were working with, see.
In the classroom and all, you knew the basic principles and so forth, but you didn't know much about the research that went behind it or the difficulties it had with it or those type of things.
There was quite a transition.
I was fortunate.
I came out in 37, like I say, it was tough, lean years, still even in New Brunswick.
See, the Depression hit the Southwest and Texas much later than it did up the country.
You know, you hear them talk about the 30s.
Well, the Depression didn't come down this way until pretty late in the 30s, and then it was very short-lived.

But I was... Before I had that difficult transition, coming to a German community, I had to remember to get specific directions, and I had to be careful because they'd start off talking in German and calling me, and I'd have to...
you know, attempt to interpret, but try to get them over to English and get those proper directions working from there.
And then, of course, I was called, again, somewhat like referred back to the various methods.
A lot of so-called ranchers and so forth at that time had had a little bit of A&M, and either it failed or
and decided to come on home and practice.
And so they had a little smattering of animal health.
There was a period in there that we were a little debated a lot about how much you teach the layman versus how much you teach the student.
And so when I came, a lot of those calls were by
Oh, I'd call them just trial run.
They just wanted to see if I knew anything.
I had some pretty good rounds with the individuals who were just tested.
One example, which is rather absurd, the one guy called me out, a couple of sick mules, or one sick mule.
Yeah, a couple of mules.
One sick mule, I said to him,
Took me down to the pit and said, there they are.
And I said, well, which one are you seeking?
He said, I don't know.
That's what I called you for.
So I decided real quick, I said, okay, here's my symbology.
Go take the temperature.
Well, then we hit it off.
We got along all right.
But those little type things.
But back to the subject matter principle, things were pretty tough, but I had an offer and a chance to go back
to Vanderbilt University on a degree, or a short course, or a seminar, or whatever you would call them in old days.
I'm a sanitary engineer.
And the state health department had indicated that they would like to have me.
And they sent me to Vanderbilt University.
I came back and joined the State Department of Health in the division of group.
Was this a short course, or was this a... Well, they were six months.
a six-month period of which we studied concrete stress.
In those days, everybody was held down, putting pit privies out for everybody, upgrading from the old open toilet to open pit.
Just a big step.
It was part of Roosevelt's program of rural upgrading and so forth.
Very fascinating.
It gave me quite an exposure to
a cross-section of individuals and another slant at a different type university, different surroundings.
One of my old classmates, for example, graduated with me.
He was a practitioner in Nashville, Tennessee, and he took me out of his way.
He was a much older person.
I'd say he was in his late 30s before he finished A&M.
And his father was, well, his name was White.
His father had invented and developed numerous veterinary instruments.
The White Instrument Company and then the White Serum Company.
But, yeah, I went through that period, came back, had a boss that was a real stickler.
Anytime I hear now about
Stadium plays, not earning their salters, all that kind of stuff.
I can look back and I was on the road many times up to six weeks without coming home because I would file an itinerary with the boss before I left Austin.
And I would meet that itinerary almost like you would a agenda.
You'd be at a certain place at a certain time, and you'd do a certain job.
And in those days, to start out, food and drug was running down the old empirical products that were available in the drugstores.
Even chasing my old alleged veterinarian who had, oh, what did he call himself?
He had a medicine show out of Waco.
had a monstrous replica of a, what's the word I want to use, a petrified log, and a little museum in it, and then he'd put on a big pitch at nighttime.
And we recorded him, and used that recorded spiel as part of his advertising program, and finally got a conviction on him.
Those type things were the beginning of Food and Drug Administration.
That will graduate on up into the passage of the state milk inspection law.
We went out and went from town to town and would sell the standard milk ordinance provided by the U.S. Public Health Service.
to set some standards and milk supplies within the communities.
Started out with the advent of the little dairy barn and the cleanliness program and the upgrading in general all the way up to TB testing.
And a very fascinating period of time.
Many experiences there where you just felt like you were beating your head against the wall.
I had one down in
Oh, I think they call it Baytown now.
It used to be Goose Creek.
Very fascinating period of time.
Many experiences there where you just felt like you were beating your head against the wall.
I had one down in, oh, I think they call it Baytown now.
It used to be Goose Creek, Baytown, and Pillay.
There were three little communities outside of Houston.
And they operated a creamery.
It was owned and operated by the Galveston Houston Brewing Company.
And we had some complaints and squawks.
And so I went into there, and it was terrible.
The creamer was horrible, but the dairies were worse.
And so I called Austin and got help, and we started inspecting dairies.
And they finally wound up with a big session at the courthouse,
And by that time, we had built a kind of a reliable spirit.
And the city health officer took on, he took to it like a duck to water.
And his pet project was a wash pan and a bar of soap in the barn where they could wash their heads between milk and so forth.
That was his pet.
Ours was all up to stainless steel containers and separate utensil rooms and things of that nature.
But anyhow, that long story short there.
Now, this was all you were working for the State Department of Health.
Well, the left was kind of mixed emotions because you couldn't tell by the response of the public here and all like that what would happen.
But when we came back at the prescribed time, it was just almost miraculous what they had done.
They'd often meet us out front, for example, and start cheering on us, pushing all the money you cost me and all that damn stuff.
Then they'd take you around back and have a whole brand new barn, followed your little plan, everything perfect.
And it gave us the inspiration then
to go on and get on to the creamer.
And we filed injunctions and everything and got to the creamer and got it all cleaned too.
But this was the early beginning of the milk inspection.
And I had the opportunity to grow up during that period.
Then came the meat inspection.
And I had the equal opportunity to grow up in that.
Meat inspection came much slower and much harder
because they had already established some forms of federal meat inspection, such as Armour and Swift in Dallas-Fort Worth, Swift and Company in San Antonio.
They had begun to build plants under federal regulation, but state had no regulations at that time.
And we had the typical situation in that with the little old
or maybe an eight by eight amortor, they called it, or butcher pit, or slaughterhouse, or whatever it was called.
And we grew up with that.
And that's when we began to use more muscle than we had with milk inspection.
Milk inspection was primarily educational.
When we got into meat inspection, it was a question of, we were coming in late, the federal had already set the basis, and so we started out by enforcement.

uh contamination uh food exposed to uh what was the word there was a basic principle in there that covered everything like grab all apple pies exposure of food to film that's it and we filed charges and we met lots of jps we learned how to show him how to fill out the
What do you call them?
Yeah, they're the forms.
You had to fill out the file charges.
And we'd help him do all that.
In many cases, he was pretty nervous.
Because I was old Bill, or Jim, he knew personally.
But it worked out into a beautiful setup.
And of course, then after I left the State Health Department,
In 1941 or thereabouts, I was given a Department of Assistant State Veteran.
Very much the same duties except with Animal World.
In South Texas, I had all of South Texas as my territory.
Now today they're called Regional Veterinarians or something like that.
But anyhow, we were subject to call any time on
Hopefully, we didn't involve ourselves in general practice or the general practitioners, except in cases of so-called disease outbreaks.
And we were allowed practice privileges at home, and that's one of the reasons I took it, because I wanted to get back home.
I stayed here then all the time.
Now, I lived here all the time, but I was gone.
so much that in 1941 I came back here.
I settled down and built a house up on a hill.
Built a little clinic in the backyard and then spent a great deal of time on the road.
Anthrax outbreaks down around Quero, sleeping sickness outbreaks around Eagle Pass, rabies outbreaks here and there in Corpus Christi.
Just all types of those type things and I grew up into that.
And I literally mean grow up, because you start out with very little experience.
And then you build on it by, oh, I had some wonderful tutors going back to A&M with Dr. Hubert Schmidt, who was head of the experiment station.
The old man taught me a lot of tricks of the philosophy of building history.
There's a man we could have gotten a lot of course.
He wrote the history, but we could have gotten a lot of oral interviews out of him.
Oh, well.
Because he died prematurely.
Well, but he was stubborn.
Much later in the game, I tried everywhere in the world to get his memoirs.
But he had that streak in him that he had worked hard and developed it, and he was holding on to those papers.
Now, what for, I don't know.
Well, some of it was published.
Oh, yeah, but not nearly the way it should have been published.
But, yeah, long story short, that, again, is him.
He helped me a lot because I had him on several of the problems I had.
In other words, as a state representative of the state veterinarian's office,
You could call upon and get assistance of a lot more people than you could probably just a general practitioner like Phil Smith at Big Spring.
There's lots of experiences out of that man.
I had a good one over at Navasota.
Bob, I'll put his name in a few minutes.
He worked for me later on.

But anyhow, I rely a whole lot upon those old-timers and their approaches to the thing because actually when you get into those type outbreaks and so forth, they're not true medical problems oftentimes as much as they are just putting two and two together and trying to come up with an approach to
What is very obvious, you can see pretty well.
You worked into a political problem, too, sometimes.
Sometimes, because a lot of the calls that you made were referred by a representative or a legislator or a governor or somebody to the state veterinarian's office.
The Office of the State Veterinarian wasn't too easy to manage then because you didn't have any representatives on the board from the professions, right?
Right, right, and very little info, or what would you call it, infrastructure relationship.
It was, oh, I don't know, just something that kind of grew with no particular principal involved.
I think, again,

it sounded like bragging or whatnot but completing this assistant 41 period assistant state veterinarian there was a transition was obviously going to take place in the state veterinarian's office and Dr. T.O.
Booth was the state veterinarian at the time and he was gearing up to go back into the military as a retreat
And he even had a double hernia repair and everything, get ready to get back in, and they took him back in.
But in the meantime, the groundwork was rolling, and a group of colleagues of mine got together in Austin.
I wasn't even present.
I didn't know what was going on, and they decided that ours should be the next state veterinary.
And it reached the stage where they were also going to

supplement my salary by entertaining to all the veterans of texas that they contributed of amount of x number of dollars or whatnot to the state led there because the salary at that time was 2760 a year plus expense but i agreed to go and give it a trial but i told them i did not want to die from
because every time I put on a necktie, that would come from Dr. So-and-so and so-and-so.
All I'd do is just go try.
So I went to Fort Worth in 1943, a state-led name, and bless his heart, Dr. Leon Cloud was, by that time, serving as the interim awaiting somebody's appointment.
And I was still basically involved as assistant to him.
And I went up
Knocked on his door, told him who I was, and he jumped up out of his chair and said, Al, I guess he came after this chair.
I said, well, I guess that's what he did, but didn't they tell you?
He said, they didn't tell me a damn thing.
So there I was, a bad bunch of my senior, and here I was just kidding.
So we had a long heart-to-heart session that he had worked for the state for a number of years.
at the fabulous salary of $166.66 a month.
And so I told him that with me coming in, I was going to try it, I was green as grass, and I would prefer to just start and stop.
And so I would recommend that he look for something to do.
Or I was going to fire him.
Well, boy, he got all bristled up and hostile and stormed out of there.
About a week later, he called me in, a guy named Steinlein.
The veterinarian had a lutealosis testing laboratory, one of the first.
Howdy.
Good evening.
How are you?
Quite good.
